\section*{Interpretation Guide}

\begin{itemize}
\item If curve $>1$ $\rightarrow$ increased firing
\item If curve $<1$ $\rightarrow$ suppression
\item If CI includes $1$ $\rightarrow$ weak or no evidence
\end{itemize}

%------------------------------------------------
\section*{Final Comparison}

Two key questions guide the comparison:

\textbf{1. Do citronellal odor puffs affect firing rate?}

Yes. All neurons show a multiplicative effect different from 1.

\textbf{2. Is the effect uniform across neurons?}

No. The direction and magnitude of the response differ.

\begin{itemize}
\item Neuron 1: increased firing during stimulus
\item Neuron 2: moderate increase during stimulus
\item Neuron 3: suppression during stimulus
\end{itemize}

%------------------------------------------------
\section*{Conclusion}

The fitted non-homogeneous Poisson process models indicate that
citronellal odor puffs affect neural firing rates. However, the effect
is not uniform across neurons. While Neurons 1 and 2 exhibit increased
activity, Neuron 3 shows suppression during the stimulus window.

This suggests that the odor stimulus produces neuron-specific
responses within the cockroach antennal lobe.

